    <h1>Is the Nasdaq Rally Becoming Too Dependent on AI?</h1>
    <p><em>Published June 25 2026</em></p>
    <p>
       The Nasdaq has continued to outperform broader equity indices, but the rally remains increasingly concentrated in a handful of large-cap AI companies. While technology has continued to attract investor inflows, broader market participation has been relatively limited, suggesting that index performance may be masking weaker underlying breadth.
    <p>
    <p>
      From a macro perspective, this concentration is worth monitoring. Historically, rallies supported by only a small group of stocks tend to become more vulnerable if market sentiment shifts or positioning becomes crowded. At the same time, investors continue to evaluate several competing macro forces. Stronger-than-expected economic data have reduced expectations for aggressive Federal Reserve rate cuts, keeping Treasury yields elevated. Higher discount rates generally create headwinds for long-duration growth stocks, whose valuations depend heavily on future cash flows.
    <p>
    <p>
      Another development I am watching is the divergence between the Nasdaq and the Dow Jones Industrial Average. While technology stocks continue to reach new highs, broader cyclical sectors have shown less momentum. This divergence may suggest that investors remain highly selective, favoring structural AI beneficiaries over economically sensitive sectors.
    <p>  
    <p>
      Going forward, I will be watching three indicators: market breadth, Treasury yields, and inflation expectations. If participation broadens while yields stabilize, the current rally could become more durable. However, if leadership remains increasingly concentrated and macro conditions tighten, elevated valuations across high-growth technology stocks could become more vulnerable to a correction.
